rity":"Medium","confidence":"high","title":"No Validation on Reward Token Addition","locations":["StaxLPStaking.sol:70"],"claim":"The addReward function allows the owner to add any address as a reward token without verifying the token exists or is valid.","impact":"An owner can add a malicious contract as a reward token. When users call getRewards, the contract will attempt to transfer from an address that may implement arbitrary behavior (e.g., reentrancy, frontrunning, or returning false on transfer). Additionally, a fake token address that doesn't implement the ERC20 interface will cause getRewards to revert, permanently locking user rewards.","paths":["1. Owner calls addReward(maliciousTokenAddress)","2. User calls getRewards() to claim rewards","3. Malicious token implementation can revert, steal tokens via callback, or implement other malicious behavior"]},{"id":"F-006","severity":"Medium","confidence":"low","title":"Missing Owner Validation in setRewardDistributor","locations":["StaxLPStaking.sol:56"],"claim":"The setRewardDistributor function does not validate that the new distributor address is different from the current one.","impact":"If the owner mistakenly calls setRewardDistributor with the current distributor address, the transaction will succeed but emit an event, potentially causing confusion in off-chain systems. More importantly, if the owner is tricked into setting a malicious distributor, all rewards can be stolen as the distributor can trigger reward distribution and front-run with reward claims.","paths":["1. Owner is phished into setting malicious address as distributor","2. Distributor calls notifyRewardAmount with minimal tokens","3. Distributor calls getRewards to claim all rewards for themselves"]},{"id":"F-007","severity":"Low","confidence":"medium","title":"Reward Token Not Removed After Period Ends","locations":["StaxLPStaking.sol:70"],"claim":"The addReward function adds reward tokens to the rewardTokens array but there is no function to remove or disable a reward token after its distribution period ends.","impact":"The rewardTokens array will grow unbounded over time as new reward tokens are added. Each call to updateReward (which is called on every stake, withdraw, and claim) iterates through the entire array. This leads to increased gas costs and eventually potential DOS when the array becomes too large to iterate within a block.","paths":["1. Owner adds many reward tokens over time","2. Array rewardTokens grows large (e.g., 100+ tokens)","3. Every stake/withdraw/getRewards operation loops through all tokens","4. Gas costs become prohibitive, users cannot interact with protocol"]},{"id":"F-008","severity":"Low","confidence":"high","title":"Potential Precision Loss in Reward Rate Calculation","locations":["StaxLPStaking.sol:201","StaxLPStaking.sol:205"],"claim":"The division operations in _notifyReward can result in precision loss when _amount is smaller than DURATION.","impact":"If the reward amount is less than the duration (e.g., 100 tokens with DURATION = 604800 seconds), the rewardRate becomes 0 due to integer division truncation. This means no rewards are distributed despite the contract receiving tokens, causing user funds to be stuck and rewards to be effectively lost.","paths":["1. Distributor calls notifyRewardAmount with amount = 100","2. DURATION = 604800 (7 days in seconds)","3. rewardRate = 100 / 604800 = 0","4. No rewards are distributed to stakers"]},{"id":"F-009","severity":"Informational","confidence":"high","title":"Missing Event Emission for Migrator Change","locations":["StaxLPStaking.sol:227"],"claim":"The setMigrator function sets the migrator address but only emits MigratorSet event if _migrator is non-zero.","impact":"If setMigrator(address(0)) is called to disable migration, no event is emitted, making it difficult to track migration state changes off-chain. Additionally, this allows the migrator to be set to address(0), which would break the migration functionality without clear indication.","paths":["1. Owner calls setMigrator(address(0)) to disable migration","2. No event is emitted","3. Off-chain systems cannot detect the change"]},{"id":"F-010","severity":"Informational","confidence":"medium","title":"Unused Migrator Can Be Set to Zero","locations":["StaxLPStaking.sol:227"],"claim":"The setMigrator function allows setting migrator to address(0), which would permanently disable migration functionality.","impact":"If the owner accidentally sets migrator to address(0), the migrateWithdraw function becomes permanently unusable (all calls will revert with 'not migrator'). While this doesn't directly lead to fund loss, it breaks the migration feature, which may be important for protocol upgrades.","paths":["1. Owner accidentally calls setMigrator(address(0))","2. migrateWithdraw always reverts with 'not migrator'","3. Protocol cannot migrate to new staking contract if needed"]}]
